* SN-26-spl-bridge-b — exercises all three SPITBOL monitor bridge sites:
*   b_vrs  (universal var-store)  → sysmv (VALUE)
*   bpf09  (function-call gate)   → sysmc (CALL)
*   retrn  (return path)          → sysmr (RETURN)
*
* Drive via:
*   MONITOR_READY_PIPE=...  MONITOR_GO_PIPE=...  MONITOR_NAMES_OUT=... \
*       /home/claude/x64/bin/sbl -bf probe.sno
*
* Expected wire (6 records on SPITBOL):
*   #0 VALUE  S    STRING(11)='hello world'      (b_vrs)
*   #1 CALL   SQR                                (bpf09)
*   #2 VALUE  SQR  INTEGER(49)                   (b_vrs inside body)
*   #3 RETURN SQR  STRING(6)='RETURN'            (retrn: &RTNTYPE)
*   #4 VALUE  N    INTEGER(49)                   (b_vrs)
*   #5 END
*
* Note SPITBOL diverges from CSNOBOL4 on this probe by ONE record:
* CSNOBOL4 fires monitor_emit_value at SJSRV1 for the pattern-substitute
* store `S 'world' = 'there'`, but SPITBOL's pattern-match store path
* doesn't traverse b_vrs.  This is a known asymmetry — captured as
* SN-26-spl-bridge-c (deferred).  For cross-oracle comparison purposes,
* either both probes drop the pattern-substitute line, or the controller
* allows the asymmetry.

        DEFINE('SQR(N)')                        :(SQR_END)
SQR     SQR = N * N                             :(RETURN)
SQR_END
        S = 'hello world'
        N = SQR(7)
END
